<paragraph blockId="28.[151,1437,152,1115]" pageId="28" pageNumber="479">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,607,152,179]" pageId="28" pageNumber="479">Female—hindwing macropterous.</emphasis>
<typeStatus box="[614,712,153,179]" pageId="28" pageNumber="479">Paratype</typeStatus>
(n = 1), length 5.85; maximum width 3.90. Similar to hindwing brachypterous specimens in general structure and coloration, except as follows: claval and intraclaval sutures, and posterior margin of embolium distinct.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="28.[151,1437,152,1115]" pageId="28" pageNumber="479">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,319,260,287]" pageId="28" pageNumber="479">Variation.</emphasis>
The mesosternal carina of three specimens deposited at the EMEC has a minute ridge entering the fossa, and the sulcus on the midline is absent.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="28" pageNumber="479" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="28.[151,1437,152,1115]" pageId="28" pageNumber="479">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,322,332,359]" pageId="28" pageNumber="479">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Specimens of 
<taxonomicName authority="Rodrigues &amp; Sites, 2019" authorityName="Rodrigues &amp; Sites" authorityYear="2019" box="[495,594,333,358]" class="Insecta" family="Naucoridae" genus="Limnocoris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="479" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nanus" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[495,594,333,358]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="479">L. nanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[604,670,333,359]" pageId="28" pageNumber="479" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[604,662,333,359]" pageId="28" pageNumber="479">n. sp</emphasis>
.
</taxonomicNameLabel>
are among the smallest of the genus, measuring 
<quantity box="[1240,1405,332,359]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.465" metricValueMax="5.85" metricValueMin="5.08" pageId="28" pageNumber="479" unit="mm" value="5.465" valueMax="5.85" valueMin="5.08">5.08–5.85 mm</quantity>
in length. The pubescent area of the propleuron is distinctly extended posteriorly along the lateral margin and the posterior margin of the propleuron is straight at mid-length. The mesosternal carina has the anterior projection distinctly developed, the fossa is uniquely shaped with the lateral margins convergent and meeting posteriorly, but open ended anteriorly with the anterior ridge entering the open anterior end of the fossa; the anterior ridge has a fine sulcus on the midline.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="28.[151,1437,152,1115]" pageId="28" pageNumber="479">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,432,548,575]" pageId="28" pageNumber="479">Comparative notes.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Rodrigues &amp; Sites, 2019" authorityName="Rodrigues &amp; Sites" authorityYear="2019" box="[438,639,549,574]" class="Insecta" family="Naucoridae" genus="Limnocoris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="479" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nanus" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[438,639,549,574]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="479">Limnocoris nanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[645,708,549,575]" pageId="28" pageNumber="479" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[645,708,549,575]" pageId="28" pageNumber="479">n. sp.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
is morphologically similar to 
<taxonomicName box="[1043,1170,548,574]" class="Insecta" family="Naucoridae" genus="Limnocoris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="479" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="insularis">
<emphasis box="[1043,1170,548,574]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="479">L. insularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": La Rivers" authorityYear="1974" box="[1183,1260,548,574]" class="Insecta" family="Naucoridae" genus="Limnocoris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="479" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lutzi">
<emphasis box="[1183,1260,548,574]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="479">L. lutzi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName authority="Rodrigues &amp; Sites, 2019" authorityName="Rodrigues &amp; Sites" authorityYear="2019" box="[1321,1408,548,574]" class="Insecta" family="Naucoridae" genus="Limnocoris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="479" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="zacki" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[1321,1408,548,574]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="479">L. zacki</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel pageId="28" pageNumber="479" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="479">n. sp.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
These species are similar in the size and general morphology of the body, including the pubescence pattern of the ventral surface. The most obvious feature to distinguish among these species is the mesosternal carina, which in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rodrigues &amp; Sites" authorityYear="2019" box="[151,248,657,682]" class="Insecta" family="Naucoridae" genus="Limnocoris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="479" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nanus">
<emphasis box="[151,248,657,682]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="479">L. nanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is unique, with the longitudinal sulcus in the anterior ridge entering the open anterior end of the fossa.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="28" pageNumber="479" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="28.[151,1437,152,1115]" pageId="28" pageNumber="479">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,353,692,719]" pageId="28" pageNumber="479">Distribution.</emphasis>
This species is distributed from northern 
<collectingCountry box="[811,932,692,719]" name="Costa Rica" pageId="28" pageNumber="479">Costa Rica</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingRegion box="[946,1079,693,719]" country="Costa Rica" name="Guanacaste" pageId="28" pageNumber="479">Guanacaste</collectingRegion>
) to the central region of 
<collectingCountry box="[1348,1437,693,719]" name="Panama" pageId="28" pageNumber="479">Panama</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingRegion box="[159,227,728,755]" country="Panama" name="Cocle" pageId="28" pageNumber="479">Coclé</collectingRegion>
) (
<figureCitation box="[250,353,728,755]" captionStart="FIGURE 20" captionStartId="42.[151,250,2002,2027]" captionTargetBox="[188,1396,171,1974]" captionTargetId="figure@42.[182,1405,164,1981]" captionTargetPageId="42" captionText="FIGURE 20. (A–B) Distribution records for species of Limnocoris in North America." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3274091/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="479">Fig. 20B</figureCitation>
). It was collected in localities with the elevation ranging from 320 to 1,371 meters.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="28" pageNumber="479" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="28.[151,1437,152,1115]" pageId="28" pageNumber="479">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,765,791]" pageId="28" pageNumber="479">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet 
<taxonomicName authority="(Latin)" authorityName="Latin" baseAuthorityName="Latin" box="[565,717,764,791]" class="Insecta" family="Naucoridae" genus="Limnocoris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="479" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nanus">
<emphasis box="[565,632,765,790]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="479">nanus</emphasis>
(Latin)
</taxonomicName>
= small or short, refers to the total length of the body of this species, which is the smallest species of 
<taxonomicName box="[568,696,801,826]" class="Insecta" family="Naucoridae" genus="Limnocoris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="479" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[568,696,801,826]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="479">Limnocoris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from North America.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
